      question: 'What\'s the difference between logs, metrics, and traces?',
      answer:
        'They answer different questions about your system:\n\n- **Logs**: "What happened on this specific request?" Per-event records, high cardinality (any fields), high storage cost, slow to query. Best for incident forensics.\n- **Metrics**: "How is the system doing overall?" Aggregated counts/durations, low cardinality (bounded labels), low storage cost, fast to query. Best for alerting and dashboards.\n- **Traces**: "Where in the distributed request did the time go?" Per-request spans showing causal flow across services. Medium cost. Best for understanding latency in microservices.\n\nA practical rule: **metrics for alerting and dashboards, logs for incident forensics, traces for distributed latency**.\n\nThe three pillars increasingly overlap — exemplars link metrics to traces, structured wide events blur logs and traces, span events are logs attached to traces. The deeper view: you have a stream of observations; logs are unfiltered, metrics are aggregations, traces are connected sequences.\n\nWhat to build first: structured logs (cheapest, immediate value), then the four golden metrics per service (latency, traffic, errors, saturation), then distributed tracing (essential once you have multiple services).\n\nIntegration is the killer feature. The correlation between signals — exemplars from metric to trace, trace_id in every log line — is what makes mature observability fast during incidents.',
