      question: 'What\'s structured logging and why does it matter?',
      answer:
        'A log entry that\'s a string is data that needs parsing every time you want to query it. A log entry that\'s a structured object (JSON, logfmt) is queryable by field directly.\n\n```json\n{"ts": "2026-05-22T14:32:01Z", "level": "info", "msg": "user logged in",\n "user_id": 42, "duration_ms": 18}\n```\n\nVersus unstructured:\n\n```\n2026-05-22 14:32:01 INFO user logged in id=42 dur=18ms\n```\n\nThe structured version supports filters like `user_id:42`, `duration_ms:>100`, grouping like `stats count() by endpoint`, and cross-service joins. The text version requires regex.\n\nWhat every entry should have:\n- **ts** (ISO-8601 UTC), **level**, **msg** (short, lowercase), **service**, **trace_id / request_id**.\n- Plus per-event fields: user_id, operation, duration_ms, error type, etc.\n- Avoid: secrets, large blobs, free-text user input as a top-level field.\n\nWhy it\'s the single biggest leverage point in logging hygiene:\n- A teammate asks "what happened to user 42 at 14:30?" — you can answer in 30 seconds with structured logs, 20 minutes with text logs.\n- Aggregations and rates become possible queries.\n- A logging library can auto-attach request context (trace_id, user_id) so every entry has it without dev effort.\n\nFormats: JSON (universal tooling support), logfmt (more readable, smaller). Both work in modern indexers. Pick one and stick with it.',
