      question: 'What are the Four Golden Signals and why those four?',
      answer:
        'From the Google SRE book — the minimum-viable monitoring set per service:\n\n1. **Latency**: time to serve a request. Split successful vs error responses (a 500 in 5ms looks healthy in raw stats but isn\'t).\n2. **Traffic**: demand. Requests per second, transactions per second.\n3. **Errors**: failed requests. By rate, not count. Split by status code / error type.\n4. **Saturation**: how "full" the service is. CPU, memory, queue depth, worker pool utilization. **Leading indicator** of failures and latency spikes.\n\nWhy these four: they cover ~80% of "is the service healthy" questions without infrastructure-specific tuning. Every service has them; you don\'t need detailed knowledge of internals to read them. They map directly to user pain (latency, errors) and pre-failure signals (traffic, saturation).\n\nWhat to alert on:\n- **Error rate spike** — % above threshold for 5+ minutes.\n- **Latency spike** — p95 above SLO for 5+ minutes.\n- **Traffic drop** — < X% of expected baseline (catches upstream outages).\n- **Saturation rising** — > 85% utilization sustained (leading indicator).\n\nWhat *not* to alert on: raw counts ("10 errors" without traffic context), single-blip spikes (use rolling windows), anything below 1% (noisier than service).\n\nThe symptom-vs-cause distinction matters: alert primarily on symptoms (users getting errors). Cause-based alerts (DB down) are supplementary — they may not fire if the cause is novel. Symptom alerts fire whenever there\'s user pain, regardless of what caused it.',
