      question: 'When should you log at INFO vs WARN vs ERROR?',
      answer:
        'The standard hierarchy:\n\n- **TRACE** — extremely detailed; rarely used.\n- **DEBUG** — diagnostic detail for developers. Off in prod.\n- **INFO** — significant events worth recording. On in prod, often sampled.\n- **WARN** — unusual but not breaking; worth attention. On.\n- **ERROR** — something failed. Should be rare; should always have action attached.\n- **FATAL** — about to crash. Should be effectively never in normal operation.\n\nPer level:\n\n- **INFO** test: "would I want to see this entry in a 10-minute window of normal traffic?" Service lifecycle events, login success, payment captured. NOT "received request" for every request (that\'s a metric).\n- **WARN**: a retry succeeded after failure; a deprecated API was called; soft threshold exceeded. Should be rare enough that an hour of WARN feed is human-readable.\n- **ERROR**: an exception you didn\'t expect; downstream failed beyond retry budget; consumer fell behind. **Crucially, ERROR means "human needs to look."**\n\nWhat is *not* an ERROR (common misuses → alert fatigue):\n- "User not found" on a lookup. That\'s a 404 outcome, not a service error.\n- "Validation failed" for bad user input. INFO at most.\n- "Rate limit exceeded" for an over-eager client. Working as designed.\n- "Timeout handled gracefully" with a fallback. WARN at most.\n\nA useful pattern: when you log at ERROR, also increment a metric. The metric drives the alert; the log explains it. Two signals from one event.\n\nFor library code: never log at ERROR for "caller passed bad input" — return an error, let the caller decide. Libraries should be quieter than apps by default.',
