      question: 'What\'s a correlation ID / trace ID and why is it the most valuable instrumentation?',
      answer:
        'A unique ID generated at the edge (gateway, load balancer, first service) that is propagated through every internal service call and recorded in every log entry related to that request.\n\nWith it: `request_id:4f3a2c1b-...` filters every log from every service touched by that request. Without it: correlating logs across services means joining by timestamp, which is unreliable and slow.\n\nThe basic flow:\n1. Edge generates an ID (or honors `X-Request-ID` from client).\n2. Every internal service-to-service call passes it (HTTP header, gRPC metadata, message header).\n3. Every log line includes it.\n4. Every trace span shares it.\n5. Every metric exemplar references it.\n\nW3C Trace Context is the standard:\n```\ntraceparent: 00-4bf92f3577b34da6a3ce929d0e0e4736-00f067aa0ba902b7-01\n             version-trace_id                       -span_id-flags\n```\n\nUse the trace_id as the correlation ID — modern OTel SDKs propagate it automatically.\n\nWhere propagation breaks (and you fix):\n- HTTP/gRPC outgoing: middleware/interceptor.\n- Message queues: include in message headers.\n- Background jobs: include in job payload.\n- Async/promise within a process: language-specific (AsyncLocalStorage, contextvars).\n\nThe speedup during investigations is 10-100×. A user reports "slow at 14:32" — find their gateway log, copy ID, search everywhere. Without ID: pivot through guessed timestamps, hope no concurrent request confuses you. With ID: instant.\n\nA simple sanity check: send a request with `X-Request-ID: testing-123`. 30 seconds later, search logs. Every service that participated should have entries.',
