      question: 'What\'s the difference between a log aggregation system\'s job and a metrics system\'s job?',
      answer:
        'Logs are events; metrics are aggregations. They\'re optimized for different access patterns.\n\n**Log aggregation systems** (Loki, Elastic, Splunk, Datadog Logs, Honeycomb-as-event-store):\n- Store each event individually with arbitrary fields.\n- Indexed for query by field (`user_id:42`, `level:error`).\n- High storage cost — every event is stored.\n- High cardinality is OK — any field can have unique values.\n- Slow for aggregate queries over millions of events.\n- Best for: "find a specific event," "what happened to request X," forensics, debugging.\n\n**Metric systems** (Prometheus, VictoriaMetrics, Mimir, Datadog Metrics):\n- Store aggregated values per time series (label combination).\n- Optimized for rate/aggregate/percentile queries.\n- Low storage cost — each series is one number per scrape.\n- **Cardinality must be bounded** — every unique label combination = a new series.\n- Very fast aggregate queries.\n- Best for: dashboards, alerts on rates/percentiles, capacity trends.\n\nWhy both: a service doing 100k req/s logs ~300k events/sec; computing real-time rate from logs requires expensive infrastructure. The same rate as a counter metric is a single number per scrape per label combination. Cost differs by orders of magnitude.\n\nWhen to convert log to metric: if you\'re counting events or aggregating durations, it\'s a metric. The log has the individual events; the metric has the rate. Often you emit both:\n\n```js\nlog.info(\'payment captured\', { amount, currency });\nmetrics.counter(\'payments_total\', { currency }).inc();\nmetrics.histogram(\'payment_amount\', { currency }).observe(amount);\n```\n\nThe log lets you debug a specific payment; the metric lets you alert on throughput.',
