      question: 'Why does Prometheus pull instead of push, and what are the trade-offs?',
      answer:
        'Prometheus chose pull-based collection for specific reasons:\n\n- **Service discovery integration.** Prometheus already needs to know targets (for label attachment); the same machinery detects "up vs down" automatically. Push doesn\'t have this signal.\n- **No unbounded buffers.** If the metrics store is down, the next scrape just returns current values. Push setups buffer; buffers grow during outages.\n- **Lower cardinality risk** at the system level. Pull means *the central system* decides what to scrape and how often; push means every client can flood the backend.\n- **Easier debugging.** `curl /metrics` on a service shows what it would report. No special tooling.\n\nTrade-offs against pull:\n\n- **Short-lived jobs** (cron, CI) might finish before any scrape. Mitigation: Pushgateway (a stateful intermediate that jobs push to, Prometheus scrapes). Acknowledged as awkward.\n- **Firewall-restricted networks.** Pull requires Prometheus to reach the service. Push is easier when services are behind strict NATs.\n- **Highly dynamic / serverless workloads.** Lambda invocations are too ephemeral for pull. Push or hybrid is cleaner.\n\nThe `/metrics` endpoint returns plain-text OpenMetrics format — each line is `metric_name{labels} value`. The service\'s job: keep this fast (under 100ms for thousands of series) and current. Prometheus scrapes on a configurable interval (upstream default 1 minute; most setups configure 15-30s); the data is the cumulative counter / current gauge / histogram bucket counts.\n\nFor most server-side workloads, pull works well. For serverless and short-lived jobs, push or OTel Collector forwarding to a push backend (or Pushgateway as a fallback) is needed.\n\nFor HA: run two identical Prometheus instances scraping the same targets, with a layer (Thanos/Cortex/Mimir) in front that merges. Single Prometheus is a SPOF; HA is two-active.',
