      question: 'What is cardinality and why is it the most important cost driver in metrics?',
      answer:
        'Cardinality is the number of unique combinations of label values for a metric. Each unique combination is a separate time series, stored independently.\n\n```\nhttp_requests_total{endpoint, method, status, region}\n# 50 endpoints × 5 methods × 10 statuses × 3 regions = 7500 series\n```\n\nAdd a `user_id` label with 1M users: 7500 × 1,000,000 = **7.5 billion series**. Each gets one value per scrape interval. The system either rejects this (Prometheus) or bills you for storage that scales linearly (Datadog, vendors).\n\nSafe labels:\n- Bounded in advance, stable over time, low cardinality (tens to low thousands).\n- Examples: endpoint, method, status, region, version, environment.\n\nUnsafe labels (cardinality dragons):\n- `user_id`, `email`, `request_id`, `url` with query strings, error message text, anything user-controllable.\n- When you want "metrics per user," you actually want **logs/traces** filtered by user_id, not a metric labeled by user_id.\n\nMitigations at platform level:\n- **Per-team cardinality budgets.** Auto-alert at 80%; reject at 100%.\n- **Linting at code review time** for new label patterns.\n- **TSDB quotas** (Mimir, Cortex, Datadog) — reject writes when a tenant exceeds.\n- **Cardinality dashboard** showing top-10 metrics by series count, top labels by unique values. Review monthly.\n- **Recording rules** that aggregate high-cardinality metrics into lower-cardinality stored series.\n\nThe failure mode is the most common: someone adds `request_id` as a label by accident; within hours the TSDB has millions of new series; storage balloons; queries slow; alerts get noisy. Recovery: roll back, drop the label at scrape-time relabel rules, wait for old series to expire.\n\nWhen you genuinely need high-cardinality breakdowns: consider VictoriaMetrics / M3 / Honeycomb-style wide events, or move that analysis to logs or traces.',
