      answer:
        'The natural trajectory: starts useful, accumulates panels, becomes a graveyard. Within a year, no one knows what half the charts mean.\n\nThree distinct dashboard uses, often confused:\n- **At-a-glance health** — "is the service okay?" 5-second read. One screen. Fixed.\n- **Investigative** — "what\'s wrong right now?" Detailed, drill-downs. Read during debugging.\n- **Exploratory** — "I want to understand a pattern." Ad-hoc; not a fixed dashboard.\n\nThe mistake is conflating them. The at-a-glance dashboard should be **above the fold with the four golden signals**:\n\n```\n┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  Latency p99    │  Error rate %  │  Throughput  │\n├─────────────────┴────────────────┴──────────────┤\n│         Saturation (CPU / Memory / Pool)         │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\nRules:\n- One service per dashboard. Don\'t mix services on the at-a-glance.\n- Big current numbers, not just charts. Operators scan for the number.\n- 8-12 panels max for at-a-glance. More = ignored.\n- Sensible defaults — 1-hour time range, sensible variables.\n\nThe investigative dashboard can have 30+ panels (per-endpoint latency, top errors by type, downstream health, deploy markers overlaid, saturation per pod, links to logs and traces).\n\nNon-negotiable: **deploy markers on every time series**. Vertical line per deploy. The single biggest investigation aid — a latency spike 3 minutes after a deploy tells the story instantly.\n\nNon-negotiable: links to runbooks and to logs/traces filtered to relevant context. Click a metric spike, jump to logs at that time. Saves minutes per investigation.\n\nDelete what isn\'t used. Grafana shows usage stats. A panel with no views in 3 months, or showing "no data" for weeks, should be removed. Dashboards aren\'t free; they take up cognitive load, get referenced in runbooks, and clutter search.\n\nThe honest test: a new on-call engineer paged at 3am, who\'s never seen the service before, can figure out what\'s wrong in 60 seconds. If not, the dashboard isn\'t doing its job.',
