      answer:
        'Five criteria every alert worth firing meets:\n\n1. **Indicates a real user problem (or imminent one).** "CPU at 50%" isn\'t a problem. "p99 over SLO for 5min" is.\n2. **Has a clear, single owner.** Five teams could own it = no one does.\n3. **Is actionable.** Recipient can do something. "Universe is broken" alerts don\'t help.\n4. **Has a runbook.** "This alert means X; investigate Y; escalate to Z." Without one, every alert is a fresh investigation.\n5. **Fires rarely.** Daily firing = the threshold is wrong, not signaling exception.\n\nIf any of these fails, **fix or delete the alert** — don\'t silence it.\n\nSymptom vs cause:\n- Symptom-based ("users are getting errors") fires on real user pain regardless of underlying cause.\n- Cause-based ("DB down") is more specific but can miss novel causes.\n- Prefer symptoms for paging; use cause-based as early-warning tickets.\n\nSeverity discipline: most "alerts" should NOT page. Only user-visible outages, fast SLO burn, or data loss risk should wake someone up. The rest are tickets for next business day.\n\nThe multi-window burn-rate pattern (Google SRE workbook): page if 5% of budget burns in 1 hour AND in 5 minutes; or 10% in 6 hours AND in 30 minutes. Sustained burn over both windows = real; single-window spike = noise.\n\nAlert payload should include: title, severity, service, current value vs threshold, recent deploys, runbook link, dashboard link. The 3am on-call gets context in seconds.\n\nCommon anti-patterns: threshold alerts without sustained window (flap); copy-pasted alerts from another service (fire wrong, get muted); per-instance alerts ("Pod-7 high CPU" — usually irrelevant; aggregate first); no deprecation (alerts about retired services).\n\nA healthy on-call rotation: 0-2 pages per week on average; all actionable; runbooks for each. Beyond that, fatigue accumulates and the next real alert gets missed.',
