      answer:
        'Technically you *could* answer "which exceptions are happening in prod and how often" from logs. In practice, error trackers do it so much better that they\'re worth their own tool.\n\nWhat they do that logs don\'t:\n\n1. **Auto-group by fingerprint.** A single bug throwing 10,000 times shows as **one issue with count 10,000**, not 10,000 separate log lines you have to mentally cluster.\n2. **Structured context per occurrence.** Each event has stack trace, local variables per frame, request details, deploy version, user context, breadcrumbs (recent events). You see *why* it failed.\n3. **First-seen / regression tracking.** Issue lifecycle: new → resolved → reopened. Tied to deploys, so you see "this regressed in v2.31."\n4. **Resolve / ignore / assign lifecycle.** Errors aren\'t just data; they\'re work items.\n5. **Source map / debug-symbol handling.** Frontend: unminifies stacks. Native: resolves debug symbols. Without this, your error tracker is half-useful.\n\nQuestions that are easy in an error tracker and hard with logs:\n- "What\'s the trend of unique errors over the last week?"\n- "Which deploy introduced this error?"\n- "Show me the local variables at the time of the exception."\n- "How many users were affected by this specific bug?"\n- "Has this exception been seen before?"\n\nIntegration shape: hook into uncaught-exception paths automatically; provide middleware for major frameworks; manually capture caught errors with extra context; send async so never blocks user requests.\n\nWhat to capture:\n- Uncaught exceptions — always.\n- Caught exceptions that represent bugs — your catch was intentional, but the bug isn\'t.\n\nWhat NOT to capture:\n- Expected validation errors (not bugs, user behavior).\n- Normal access-denied 401s/404s.\n- Errors with PII you can\'t redact.\n\nAlerting: alert on **new issues** (regression catcher), **spike detection** (existing issue suddenly common), and **regression reappearance** (resolved issue back). Don\'t alert on raw error counts; that\'s noise.\n\nVolume control at scale: server-side sampling for repeated errors, client-side rate limit, ignore lists. Don\'t over-sample — losing the long-tail single-user bugs defeats the purpose.',
