      answer:
        'Both. They answer different questions.\n\n**Synthetic** = scheduled probes from outside, against the real service. Tells you what a user *would* experience if they tried now.\n\n**RUM** = data from real users\' actual experiences. Tells you what they *did* experience.\n\n| | Synthetic | RUM |\n|---|---|---|\n| Detects outage | Yes, before users notice | Cannot — no users = no data |\n| Catches weird device bugs | No | Yes |\n| Geographic coverage | Configured regions | Wherever users actually are |\n| Network variety | Probe network only | Real ISPs, mobile networks |\n| Catches DNS / cert / CDN issues | Yes | Sometimes (after impact) |\n\nWhy "outside" matters for synthetic: probes from inside the VPC tell you internal services are up. Probes from outside tell you the customer can reach you. The space between (DNS, TLS, CDN, LB, geo-routing) is full of bugs.\n\nSynthetic flavors:\n- **Uptime checks** (simple): HTTP at intervals from multiple regions. Cheap, catches most "service down" cases. Tools: Pingdom, Cloudflare healthchecks, UptimeRobot.\n- **Multi-step / scripted**: full user flows via Playwright/Puppeteer or HTTP scripts. Catches "200 OK home page with broken login."\n\nWhat to probe (don\'t probe everything; you\'re not load-testing):\n- Home page loads.\n- Login flow end-to-end.\n- Primary user action.\n- API auth endpoint.\n- 1-2 representative critical endpoints.\n\nCommon pitfalls:\n- Probes from a single region (geographic blind spots).\n- Synthetics that accumulate side effects (test orders polluting prod). Use tagged test accounts; clean up.\n- No alerting on synthetic failures.\n- Testing staging only.\n\nFailure modes synthetics catch best: cert expiration, DNS issues, CDN misconfigs, bad deploys breaking public endpoints, third-party dependencies affecting your flow, regional outages.\n\nReasonable budget: a few dozen simple checks every minute + a handful of scripted browser tests every 5-10 minutes. Total: $100-500/month with typical vendors.\n\nAt scale, deploy a vendor + maintain a few critical synthetic tests yourself. The tests prevent outages; the vendor provides geographic reach.',
