      question: 'What is a span, and how do distributed traces actually get assembled across services?',
      answer:
        'A **span** is the fundamental unit of distributed tracing: a named operation with start time, end time, parent, attributes, and events. A trace is a directed tree of spans sharing the same `trace_id`.\n\n```\ntrace_id: 4f3a... (one per request)\n├─ root span: "GET /products"     service=gateway   0ms - 250ms\n│  ├─ span: "fetch product"       service=catalog   5ms - 240ms\n│  │  ├─ span: "db query"         service=catalog   8ms - 65ms\n│  │  └─ span: "enrich pricing"   service=pricing   71ms - 235ms\n│  └─ span: "render response"     service=gateway   241ms - 249ms\n```\n\nEach span has trace_id, span_id, parent_span_id, name, timing, attributes (`http.method`, `db.statement`, etc.), events (timestamped log-like sub-events), and status.\n\nAssembly across services requires **context propagation** — the trace_id and parent span_id are passed through every service boundary:\n\n- HTTP: via the W3C `traceparent` header.\n  ```\n  traceparent: 00-4bf92f3577b34da6a3ce929d0e0e4736-00f067aa0ba902b7-01\n               ver-trace_id                       -span_id          -flags\n  ```\n- gRPC: via metadata.\n- Message queues: via message headers (Kafka headers, RabbitMQ headers, SQS message attributes).\n- Background jobs: passed in job payload.\n- Within a process: AsyncLocalStorage (Node), contextvars (Python), Context (Go), etc.\n\nOpenTelemetry auto-instrumentation libraries inject and read these headers automatically. Without proper propagation, a trace breaks: the downstream becomes its own disconnected trace. (Mitigation: span links, which note "this trace was caused by that one" without parent/child semantics.)\n\nThe data model is standardized as OpenTelemetry — use OTel SDKs.\n\nWhat traces are best at:\n- "Where did time go in this slow request?" — Gantt-style view shows the wide bar.\n- "What did this request actually call?" — runtime dependency graph.\n- "Why did it fail?" — the span where error originated has the stack; ancestors show the chain.\n\nWhat they\'re bad at:\n- High-volume aggregate analysis (use metrics).\n- Anything sampled out (if 90% sampled-out, the request the user just complained about probably isn\'t in the store).\n- Intra-process performance (use a profiler).',
